The primary intervention — the structured cue protocol introduced in subsection 3.2 — produced a mean accuracy of 74.8% (SD = 8.1) among treated participants, a 13.5 percentage point increase over baseline (t(83) = 6.44, p < .001, Cohen's d = 0.71). The effect is large by conventional standards, and its phase-specificity is telling: gains were concentrated in the recall phase rather than the encoding phase, as confirmed by phase-disaggregated scoring. The protocol was doing something structurally targeted, not simply making everything easier. But a large aggregate effect with a structurally targeted mechanism and a heterogeneous baseline is precisely the profile that should prompt suspicion about what the average is averaging over. The main effect answers whether the protocol works. It does not answer whether it works the same way for everyone — and given the baseline distribution, there is no principled reason to assume it does.

To test that suspicion, a moderated regression model was specified with working-memory capacity as the moderator, operationalized as digit-span score (range 4–9) and entered as a continuous variable alongside intervention condition and their product term. Participant working-memory capacity interacted significantly with intervention condition (β = 0.31, SE = 0.08, p = .001). Among participants with digit-span scores below the sample median of 6.5, the protocol produced gains of only 7.2 percentage points; above the median, gains averaged 18.9 points. The protocol does not compensate for limited capacity — it multiplies the capacity that is already there. This is the result the preceding findings were building toward — and it reframes them. The baseline heterogeneity was not noise to be averaged away; it was signal. The large main effect was not evidence of a general-purpose tool; it was the aggregate of two meaningfully different effects. The argument the data have been making, from the first descriptive statistic onward, is that the protocol's value is conditional — and it is only at this stage that the condition becomes visible. That conditionality is not a limitation to be acknowledged and set aside; it is the finding that determines whether the protocol warrants broad rollout or targeted deployment to participants most positioned to benefit from it.</draft>

